{"metadata": {"synopsis": "Workaholic Lisa (Mary Stuart Masterson) long ago shut down emotionally, retreating into a shell during her painful childhood. Career is foremost in her mind and romance the very last thing. That changes when she receives a stunning bouquet of flowers from a secret admirer. When she asks the florist, Lewis (Christian Slater), where they came from, he admits they are from him. Lewis sweeps Lisa off her feet and seems to be her perfect man. But he too harbors a painful past.", "rating": "19", "genre": "Drama/Romance", "runtime": "1h 27m", "director": "Michael Goldenberg", "studio": "NewLineCinema,JunoPix", "theater_date": "", "dvd_date": "Jul 27, 1999", "box_office": "$19.0M"}, "reviews": {"reviews": ["A good, even beautiful, premise, but this romance is stronger on ambience than development.", "", "A very sweet movie, Slater and Masterson encompass real sparks", "", "", "", "", "", "", "", "Bed of Roses tells a sappy story about two sad sacks who get more or less what they deserve -- each other.", "Don't blame the leads, but the movie has less emotional resonance than an old FTD florist commercial with Merlin Olsen.", "", "", "", ""], "rating": ["", "C-", "3/5", "2/5", "3/5", "1.5/4", "2/5", "2/4", "2/4", "3/4", "2/4", "2/4", "2.5/4", "6", "2.5/4", "C-"], "fresh": ["rotten", "rotten", "fresh", "rotten", "fresh", "rotten", "rotten", "rotten", "rotten", "fresh", "rotten", "rotten", "rotten", "rotten", "rotten", "rotten"], "critic": ["Quentin Curtis", "Lisa Schwarzbaum", "Caffeinated Clint", "Emanuel Levy", "Rob Thomas", "Jeanne Aufmuth", "Christopher Null", "James Kendrick", "Susan Stark", "James Berardinelli", "Roger Ebert", "Mike Clark", "Steve Rhodes", "Brian Webster", "Madeleine Williams", ""], "publisher": ["data-qa=\"review-critic-publication\">Independent on Sunday", "data-qa=\"review-critic-publication\">Entertainment Weekly", "data-qa=\"review-critic-publication\">Tsunami Magazine", "data-qa=\"review-critic-publication\">EmanuelLevy.C